		   <table class="mform"  border="0" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="0" width="100%">
		   <tr><td class="headerrow" colspan="2" class="mform" valign="top">Best Setup/Strategy for a Pally<br clear=all>
		   <span class="sm">Posted @ Thu, Aug 16th 1:10 PM 2001 </span><span id="notbold">| <span class=sm>IP: Logged</span> | <a href="/db/classes.html?class=6&mid=99798180983019&post=1"><a class=sm href="/db/classes.html?class=6&mid=99798180983019&num=2&post=1&replyto=99798180983019"><img src=/shared/reply_to_thread_ico.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=11 width=17> Reply to this</a></a>   <a name=99798180983019></a></small></td></tr>
		   <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=83710"><span id=Scholar>jcasetnl</span></a><b><span id=Scholar><br>Scholar</span></b><br><img src=/shared/user_star_ico.gif height=9 width=9><br>153 posts
		   <br><nobr><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good [4.25]</nobr><br><br><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%"><p>I've been playing a paladin for a couple months now to level 20 and here's what I've learned about them so far.&nbsp;&nbsp;Be aware that I have no idea what the high level game is like and that going by this stuff might result in a character that is useless at really high levels.  <br><br>First, Paladins are more fighter than cleric and you should keep this in mind with both your race choice and your bonus point distribution.  In my opinion, Dwarves make the best pallys since they're significantly tougher than all the other races.  Also, the majority of pally spells that are usable in a fight take little mana.  Most of your mana depletion will occur after the fight when you help out with healing.  So it's pointless to adjust stats for a high mana pally.<br><br>Second, the best use of a pally is in a group, but a pally can be solo'd by a smart and patient player.  There's generally some confusion about how to do this exactly so I'll explain.<br><br>In order to solo a pally you must focus significantly on weopons and items that will give you an advantage *in a fight*, especially after Level 9.  This is when the paladin and warrior start to take different paths and the mobs become more difficult to solo and tend to agro more. This is also when running to gaurds or the zone becomes less viable since either there are no gaurds or mobs will start casting and rooting.  Don't waste your money on trade skills or other superflous endeavors.  Wait until you are effective in battle and then go back and learn them.  <br><br>Because you are not as powerful a melee as a warrior, you will find yourself struggling against blues around level 12 unless you are decently equipped.  I found that unless I joined a group at about level 15, I could not advance.  I'd kill four mobs then die and my experience would drop back to where it was before or even lower.  It would take as much as two bubbles of health to kill a green that would still give exp.  Despite getting a much better healing spell and Ward Undead I would still need to fight blues until I had about 1.5 bubbles of health left.  Sometimes I'd win and sometimes I'd have to run.  Either way it was very slow going with my mino axe, which maxed at 17hp/hit.<br><br>So from 15 to 18 I had to group, and in so doing I picked up a lot of cash which I used to buy  excellent weopons (13/31 1hs 20/45 2hs) for my level.  This made soloing possible again.  <br><br>The next thing about soloing a pally is to use your spells effectively.  You have got to use these spells for all they're worth (cause most aren't worth the paper they're printed on) and know when *not* to use them.  Examples:  <br><br>-Heal after a battle, even though it's tedious.  A lot of your battles will go to the wire.  At ten points a pop that minor heal is a bear, I know.  And don't forget to cast courage on yourself!  Create a hotkey for yaulp and stick it right next to your Bash button.  Bash and yaulp throughout the fight.  <br><br>-Spells like flash of light and fear undead can be extremely dangerous.  If you are up against an undead and you are clearly going to get hammered then your best strategy is to try to fear him.  Fear takes awhile to cast but you can ussually get it off eventually despite taking hits.  This is a good use of fear, but note that you will almost never be able to get it off if you're being hit by more than one mob.  A *bad* use of fear is in an area such as unrest where there are a ton of baddies and trains are common.  When your fear spell wears off that skelly is going to agro everyone and his brother on you.  <br><br>-Flash of light is a very similar spell to Fear Undead except for three key differences: 1) it works on a wider variety of mobs, 2) if a mob is already hitting you when you cast it on him, he will continue to hit you until you move away.  Fear undead will cause the undead mob to turn tail and run. 3) Flash of Light seems to cause less agro when it wears off, but rest assured, that mob *will* be coming after you.  <br><br>Both of these spells are great pullers when you are confident that you will win against a particular group of mobs.  Like if you're fighting low blues with a group, volume is a good thing.  These spells will cause the mob to run from you and pick up some friends while you rejoin your group and get ready for the battle.  Now, if you want to pull a single yellow or red, these are bad to use...<br><br>Finally, you have to seek out good solo spots.  Dungeons are about the worst place to go.  You won't be able to hang until you way outclass the mobs that live there (and thus you won't get exp).  Note, though, that the good money is often in dungeons so it's a trade-off.  Areas like the north desert of Ro are great solo spots for a level 12 - 15, oasis of mar is good around 17.  This is true for all classes, though, not just pallys.<br><br>Now, on the flipside of things, Pallys are MUCH better in groups.  The ideal role is as a secondary tank but they can also play primary when they are two or three levels above the rest of the group and mobs.  <br><br>As a secondary, pallys are most effective because:<br><br>-If the mob(s) are focused on the primary tank, the pally is free to cast things like ward and fear to aid in crowd control and tack on extra damage.  <br>-The pally can assist in healing the primary tank(s)<br>- The pally can remove DOTs like poison and disease during the fight, reducing mob casters' effectiveness.<br>- Pallys are very 'self-sufficient' - they can heal, cure, defend and take care of themselves for the most part.<br><br>The key is good communication between the pally and the main tank.  <br><br>In a group, the most dangerous time for a pally is when he's forced to cure himself (like if the cleric is OOM).  He then must med which takes him out of the fight and the main tank is now pulling not double - but potentially triple duty.  This is because the pally won't be able to heal him, remove diseases, or tack on damage. The main tank is essentially soloing at that point, unless the rest of the group can fill the gap with added nukes and charms.<br><br>Thankfully, this downtime is ussually relatively short.  A paladin is pretty safe at 3/5 mana most of the time.  <br><br>I hope I've given some good info on how to use a pally effectively.  Of course, some of this info may be incorrect and their's no substitute for good ol' fashion experience.</p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform"><table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width="100%"><tr><td id=fs8></td><td align=right id=fs8 >2 Replies</td></tr></table></td></tr></table><tr><td>
